# TypeScript Utility Types

Utility types are **pre-built generic type transformers** in the TypeScript standard library. The mental model: they are functions at the type level. You pass a type in, you get a modified type out — without writing any runtime code.

```
Value-level function:          Type-level utility:

function omit(obj, keys) {     type Omit<T, K> = ...
  ...                            ↑
}                           TypeScript evaluates this
                            at compile time, not runtime
omit(user, ['password'])    Omit<User, 'password'>
  → runtime object            → compile-time type
```

## Partial and Required

```ts
interface User {
  name: string;
  age: number;
  email: string;
}

// Partial<T> — makes every property optional
type UserDraft = Partial<User>;
// { name?: string; age?: number; email?: string }

// Use case: update/patch functions — you only need the changed fields
function updateUser(id: string, changes: Partial<User>): void {
  // 'changes' can have any subset of User fields
}

// Required<T> — makes every property required (removes ?)
interface Config { host?: string; port?: number; }
type FullConfig = Required<Config>;
// { host: string; port: number } — no more optionals
```

## Readonly

```ts
// Readonly<T> — makes every property readonly
type ImmutableUser = Readonly<User>;
// { readonly name: string; readonly age: number; readonly email: string }

const u: ImmutableUser = { name: 'Alice', age: 30, email: 'a@b.com' };
u.name = 'Bob';  // ✗ Error — cannot assign to readonly property

// Commonly used with arrays:
type ReadonlyArr = ReadonlyArray<number>;
const arr: ReadonlyArr = [1, 2, 3];
arr.push(4);     // ✗ Error — no mutating methods on ReadonlyArray
arr[0] = 99;     // ✗ Error — index assignment disallowed
```

## Pick and Omit

```ts
interface User {
  id: string;
  name: string;
  email: string;
  password: string;
  createdAt: Date;
}

// Pick<T, K> — keep only the listed keys
type PublicUser = Pick<User, 'id' | 'name' | 'email'>;
// { id: string; name: string; email: string }

// Omit<T, K> — keep everything EXCEPT the listed keys
type SafeUser = Omit<User, 'password'>;
// { id: string; name: string; email: string; createdAt: Date }

// Mental model:
// Pick = whitelist (say what you WANT)
// Omit = blacklist (say what you DON'T WANT)
```

```
Pick vs Omit visual:

  User = { id, name, email, password, createdAt }

  Pick<User, 'id' | 'name'>       Omit<User, 'password'>
  ┌──────────────────────────┐   ┌──────────────────────────┐
  │  id     ✓  keep          │   │  id        ✓  keep       │
  │  name   ✓  keep          │   │  name      ✓  keep       │
  │  email     discard       │   │  email     ✓  keep       │
  │  password  discard       │   │  password  ✗  remove     │
  │  createdAt discard       │   │  createdAt ✓  keep       │
  └──────────────────────────┘   └──────────────────────────┘
```

## Record

```ts
// Record<K, V> — create an object type mapping keys K to values V
type Status = 'idle' | 'loading' | 'success' | 'error';
type StatusConfig = Record<Status, { label: string; color: string }>;

const statusMap: StatusConfig = {
  idle:    { label: 'Idle',    color: 'grey'   },
  loading: { label: 'Loading', color: 'blue'   },
  success: { label: 'Done',    color: 'green'  },
  error:   { label: 'Failed',  color: 'red'    },
  // TypeScript enforces ALL four keys are present
};

// Record with string keys:
type Cache = Record<string, unknown>;  // any string key → unknown value
```

## Exclude and Extract (union operators)

```ts
type T = 'a' | 'b' | 'c' | 'd';

// Exclude<T, U> — remove from T the members assignable to U
type WithoutAB = Exclude<T, 'a' | 'b'>;  // 'c' | 'd'

// Extract<T, U> — keep ONLY the members assignable to U
type JustAB = Extract<T, 'a' | 'b'>;     // 'a' | 'b'

// Practical use — filter a union by category:
type Event = MouseEvent | KeyboardEvent | FocusEvent;
type PointerEvents = Extract<Event, MouseEvent>;  // MouseEvent
```

## NonNullable

```ts
// NonNullable<T> — removes null and undefined from T
type MaybeString = string | null | undefined;
type DefiniteString = NonNullable<MaybeString>;  // string

// Useful when you've already null-checked and want TypeScript to know:
function process<T>(val: T | null): NonNullable<T> {
  if (val === null) throw new Error();
  return val as NonNullable<T>;  // safe after the guard
}
```

## ReturnType and Parameters

```ts
// ReturnType<F> — extract what a function returns
function getUser() {
  return { id: '1', name: 'Alice', age: 30 };
}
type UserReturnType = ReturnType<typeof getUser>;
// { id: string; name: string; age: number }

// Parameters<F> — extract the parameter types as a tuple
function add(a: number, b: number): number { return a + b; }
type AddParams = Parameters<typeof add>;
// [a: number, b: number]

// These are vital for typing wrappers without re-declaring signatures:
function logged<T extends (...args: any[]) => any>(
  fn: T
): (...args: Parameters<T>) => ReturnType<T> {
  return (...args) => {
    console.log('calling with', args);
    return fn(...args);
  };
}
```

## Utility Types Cheatsheet

```
┌────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
│ Utility Type       │ What it does                      │
├────────────────────┼───────────────────────────────────┤
│ Partial<T>         │ All props optional                │
│ Required<T>        │ All props required                │
│ Readonly<T>        │ All props readonly                │
│ Pick<T, K>         │ Keep only keys K                  │
│ Omit<T, K>         │ Remove keys K                     │
│ Record<K, V>       │ Object with keys K, values V      │
│ Exclude<T, U>      │ Remove union members in U         │
│ Extract<T, U>      │ Keep union members in U           │
│ NonNullable<T>     │ Remove null and undefined         │
│ ReturnType<F>      │ Return type of function F         │
│ Parameters<F>      │ Params of function F as tuple     │
│ InstanceType<C>    │ Instance type of class C          │
│ Awaited<T>         │ Unwrap Promise<T> recursively     │
└────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘
```

## Common Pitfalls
- `Partial<T>` is shallow — nested object props remain required. Use a recursive DeepPartial for truly optional deep objects
- `Readonly<T>` is also shallow — nested arrays can still be mutated
- `Pick` and `Omit` don't work on union types the way you'd expect — use `Extract`/`Exclude` for unions
- `ReturnType<typeof fn>` requires `typeof` — `ReturnType<fn>` is an error (fn is a value, not a type)
- `Record<string, T>` makes TypeScript believe every string key exists — use `Record<string, T | undefined>` or an index signature with undefined to be honest

## Connections
- **ts-generics** — all utility types are generic; understanding generics is prerequisite
- **ts-advanced-types** — utility types are implemented as mapped types and conditional types
- **ts-interfaces-types** — Pick/Omit operate on interface shapes
- **react-hooks** — Partial<State> is the classic pattern for setState with partial updates

